      <projectDesc>
        <p>Temporal information is encoded in human languages by two related yet distinct linguitic categories: tense and aspect. While tense and aspect are both temporal notions, they are different in nature. Tense is related to the temporal location whereas aspect is concerned with the temporal shape of a situation. English grammatically marks both tense and aspect while Chinese is a tenseless language that only marks aspect. This research project uses an English and a Chinese corpus to investigate how temporal and aspect meanings are expressed in the two typologically different languages..</p>
      </projectDesc>
